# Layout Architecture & Responsive Matrix

## Core Philosophy (CRITICAL)
- Structural visibility (Sidebar, Top Menu, Drawer) **MUST NEVER** be controlled by CSS media queries (e.g., `max-lg:hidden`, `md:flex`).
- UI rendering is a deterministic function of the JS State Machine. All structural responsive logic MUST be driven by `@src/stores/modules/device.ts` and calculated in the layout orchestrator (`LayoutAdmin.tsx`).

## [LAW] Layout Container Exclusivity
- Top-level width archetypes (`layout-full`, `layout-container`, `layout-narrow`, `layout-screen`) are **MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE**.
- **FORBIDDEN:** NEVER nest these classes inside each other (e.g., `<div class="layout-container"><div class="layout-narrow">` is strictly illegal).
- You must CHOOSE ONE to define the page's horizontal boundary.

## The Golden Two-Dimensional Matrix
Layout adaptability relies on BOTH Physical Device Type (`deviceStore.type`) AND Viewport Width (`deviceStore.width`).
- **Mobile (`type === 'Mobile'`):** ALWAYS Drawer (Hamburger) mode.
- **Tablet (`type === 'Tablet'`):** Drawer ONLY IF `width < BREAKPOINTS.md` (768px). Otherwise, normal structural menus.
- **PC (`type === 'PC'`):** NEVER Drawer. PC devices strictly preserve their layout (Sidebar/Top Menu) regardless of viewport squeeze.

## Anti-Patterns (FORBIDDEN)
- ❌ Using UnoCSS responsive classes to hide/show structural `<aside>`, `<header>`, or `<nav>` elements.
- ❌ Using monolithic breakpoints (like `< lg`) to force PC into mobile layouts.
